text.Taxonomy and naming:
Eucalyptus ligulata was first formally described in 1974 by the botanist Ian Brooker from a specimen collected by Keith M. Allan near a beach in the Cape Le Grand National Park. The description was published in the journal Nuytsia. The specific epithet (ligulata) is a Latin word meaning "strap-shaped".In 2002, Dean Nicolle described two subspecies and the names have been accepted by the Australian Plant Census:
Eucalyptus ligulata Brooker subsp. ligulata;
Eucalyptus ligulata subsp. stirlingica Nicolle has shorter pedicels and narrower flower buds with an operculum that is much longer than the floral cup of the autonym.
